# level1

We first decompile the code into C.

We can see that we can trigger a segmentation fault with 76 characters of input. We also see that the program has a function named `run` that executes a shell, but it is not accessible from `main` (unlike the level before).

So we will need to use a stack-based buffer overflow to call that function.

To do so, first we need to know the address of that function. The offset in this case is easy—76 bytes—and that is all.

First, we get the address of the `run` function by running the program through GDB and extracting the value with `info functions`:
```text
0x08048444
```

So we can write a python command to create our custom payload using the `[::-1]` slice to reverse the endianness of the address:
```bash
python -c 'print "a" * 76 + "\x08\x04\x84\x44"[::-1]' > payload
```

And then we execute the payload with pipes to exploit the binary:
```bash
(cat payload; cat) | ./level1
```

### Why we can replace the address
To understand why this works, we need to understand the concept of the return instruction (`ret`). When a return is called, the stack is used to change the execution pointer. In this case, the offset of the input buffer matches the offset to the saved return address (EIP). While this is not always the case, we need to verify how the base pointer (EBP) is set up and calculate the offset accordingly.
